issue.title: Restoring rancher mgr from minio/s3 backup results in "creatorID annotation cannot be changed" for vsphere downstream
issue.body:
**Rancher Server Setup**
- Rancher version: 2.7.4
- Installation option (Docker install/Helm Chart): helm chart
- Kubernetes Version and Engine: v1.24.15+rke2r1 

**Describe the bug**
When restoring the Rancher mgr to a new cluster with same Rancher/k8s version, the restore runs successfully for a bit then fails while trying to restore resources for a downstream cluster (vmwarevsphereconfigs, clusters) in fleet-default namespace. The error is 'Error restoring namespaced resources [error restoring qamachine of type rke-machine-config.cattle.io/v1, Resource=vmwarevsphereconfigs: restoreResource: err updating resource admission webhook "rancher.cattle.io.rke-machine-config.cattle.io" denied the request: creatorID annotation cannot be changed'. Also see 'error restoring qacluster of type provisioning.cattle.io/v1, Resource=clusters: restoreResource: err updating resource admission webhook "rancher.cattle.io.clusters.provisioning.cattle.io" denied the request: creatorID annotation cannot be changed'. The restore then re-queues and fires again. If restore is manually terminated after this error, downstream becomes healthy. Not sure if restore is fully complete or not.

**To Reproduce**
Steps to reproduce the behavior:
1. Deploy HA Rancher cluster, install Rancher Backup
2. Deploy a downstream vsphere cluster
3. Create a one time backup to Minio (S3) target
4. Destroy HA Rancher cluster, rebuild it with same Rancher version and k8s version, install Rancher Backup
5. Create a restore resource, start restore. Restore starts successfully.
6. Receive an error that content cannot be created in namespace cluster-fleet-default-qacluster-f3af050068a3 because the namespace is terminating. Manually delete the namespace, otherwise this repeats infinitely (delete succeeds). Restore re-queues automatically.
7. The next automatic run of the restore gives the errors in description. The (existing) downstream cluster state in UI shows "In Progress" and "Cluster generation is 1, but latest observed generation is 2".
8. If I delete the restore resource at this point, the downstream cluster runs through a quick 'provisioning' run, but doesn't redeploy any machines, then goes active. Everything seems ok.

**Expected behavior**
The restore should complete and the existing downstream vsphere cluster should appear Active. Terminating a restore prior to completion seems sketchy to me.

**Screenshots**
If applicable, add screenshots to help explain your problem.

**Additional context**
We deploy our downstream vsphere clusters via Helm chart installed to fleet-default (e.g. https://github.com/rancher/cluster-template-examples)

comment.body: @jbartlet Sorry for the late reply, the issue is simply that Rancher was installed before you ran the restore. If you are restoring to a cluster with Rancher running make sure to either run the restore from the UI and have prune enabled, or if installing to a fresh cluster to only install the rancher helm chart _**after**_ the restore is complete.

issue.title: [Feature Request] Restore Resource Patches
issue.body:
## Idea
Restore Patches would be an enhancement for the backup restore operator allowing users to configure patches to be applied to the resources being restored to the cluster. The idea came up in a discussion regarding solutions to [this issue](https://github.com/rancher/rancher/issues/42631). 

### Reasoning
The feature will allow users to do "mutating" migrations, enabling them to fix potential issues that may occur when migration to different underlying infrastructures/kubernetes distros/hosts. It also gives our support team greater capabilities around modifying backups while also cutting down the amount of work needed by customers when sending backing and forth backup tar files.

### User Experience
***NOTE:*** This is a draft proposal and has not been approved, nor is it a design document either.
The restore patches would be either and extension to the restore CRD or have it's own CRD. They would define a resource selection, path to field which would need to be patched, and an action. Users would be able to create a set of patches to be applied upon restoring the resources. Some potential requirements for the patch are:
- It should not affect the backup file stored in persistant storage to avoid corrupting important backups
- Should happen in memory 
- Should have robust error handling so the user can make mistakes in the patch without damaging the underlying cluster.

issue.title: unable to restore rancher using backup operator with local-path
issue.body:
Hi,

Following steps that I performed to restore my rancher local cluster to an old state. 
- Installed Rancher on k3s single node cluster 
- Installed Rancher backup operator in the local cluster with local-path storage class
- Imported another k3s cluster in Rancher
- Took the backup of local cluster with default storage (local-path)
- Deleted the imported k3s cluster
- Restored the backup that was taken before deleting downstream imported cluster.  

Rancher Application took some time to start and after some time, the downstream imported cluster is visible but with unavailable status and even the rancher pods are restarting from time to time.
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/45073684/199662570-0d8a12b0-6361-4c2e-ab5d-9ed3706a7b67.png)

comment.body: Is there any official way to skip the cluster that was deleted in the restore or do we need to manually delete the resources from the `tar.gz` of the backup?

issue.title: Restoring rancher mgr from minio/s3 backup results in "creatorID annotation cannot be changed" for vsphere downstream
issue.body:
**Rancher Server Setup**
- Rancher version: 2.7.4
- Installation option (Docker install/Helm Chart): helm chart
- Kubernetes Version and Engine: v1.24.15+rke2r1 

**Describe the bug**
When restoring the Rancher mgr to a new cluster with same Rancher/k8s version, the restore runs successfully for a bit then fails while trying to restore resources for a downstream cluster (vmwarevsphereconfigs, clusters) in fleet-default namespace. The error is 'Error restoring namespaced resources [error restoring qamachine of type rke-machine-config.cattle.io/v1, Resource=vmwarevsphereconfigs: restoreResource: err updating resource admission webhook "rancher.cattle.io.rke-machine-config.cattle.io" denied the request: creatorID annotation cannot be changed'. Also see 'error restoring qacluster of type provisioning.cattle.io/v1, Resource=clusters: restoreResource: err updating resource admission webhook "rancher.cattle.io.clusters.provisioning.cattle.io" denied the request: creatorID annotation cannot be changed'. The restore then re-queues and fires again. If restore is manually terminated after this error, downstream becomes healthy. Not sure if restore is fully complete or not.

**To Reproduce**
Steps to reproduce the behavior:
1. Deploy HA Rancher cluster, install Rancher Backup
2. Deploy a downstream vsphere cluster
3. Create a one time backup to Minio (S3) target
4. Destroy HA Rancher cluster, rebuild it with same Rancher version and k8s version, install Rancher Backup
5. Create a restore resource, start restore. Restore starts successfully.
6. Receive an error that content cannot be created in namespace cluster-fleet-default-qacluster-f3af050068a3 because the namespace is terminating. Manually delete the namespace, otherwise this repeats infinitely (delete succeeds). Restore re-queues automatically.
7. The next automatic run of the restore gives the errors in description. The (existing) downstream cluster state in UI shows "In Progress" and "Cluster generation is 1, but latest observed generation is 2".
8. If I delete the restore resource at this point, the downstream cluster runs through a quick 'provisioning' run, but doesn't redeploy any machines, then goes active. Everything seems ok.

**Expected behavior**
The restore should complete and the existing downstream vsphere cluster should appear Active. Terminating a restore prior to completion seems sketchy to me.

**Screenshots**
If applicable, add screenshots to help explain your problem.

**Additional context**
We deploy our downstream vsphere clusters via Helm chart installed to fleet-default (e.g. https://github.com/rancher/cluster-template-examples)

comment.body: @eliyamlevy OK, that I had obviously not figured out, as I did install Rancher then run the restore. So, if we have a disaster happen and the original HA Rancher cluster is lost, the Rancher backups can't be used for recovery? The doc mentions 'A restore refers to restoring a backup to the same cluster it was taken from.' but in the same section (next bullet) mentions '...This allows you to install Rancher Backups again and restore to a completely fresh cluster.' I am clearly having issues connecting the dots here.

issue.title: Migration from k3s local cluster to rke2 breaks with config restore
issue.body:
**Rancher Server Setup**
- Rancher version: 2.6.9
- Installation option (Docker install/Helm Chart): rancher-latest/rancher --version 2.6.9
- Kubernetes Version and Engine: v1.23.13+rke2r1

**Describe the bug**
TL;DR - migration from RMS on a k3s local cluster to use rke2 as the local cluster causes the operator to "register" the local rke2 cluster as k3s, triggering the automated upgrade on the local cluster to try to "upgrade" rke2 to k3s, to put the local cluster in the same engine version as when the backup was created. This breaks RMS.
 
Long story - We wanted to migrate our Rancher RMS from a k3s single-node cluster, to an rke2 single-node cluster. When we backed up the RMS configs from k3s cluster (backed up using the backup-restore-operator), and then applied the configs to the new rke2 cluster for migration. When we applied the configs, Rancher suddenly decided the rke2 local cluster was a k3s cluster, and tried to apply the "update strategy" to upgrade the "local" cluster from what it was at (`v1.23.13+rke2r1`) to what the local cluster was at when it was backed up (`v1.24.6+k3s1`). Obviously, the automated upgrade from rke2 to k3s fails, but it keeps the local cluster in "unscheduleable" status until the failing upgrade completes, which never completes.

**To Reproduce**
Steps to reproduce the behavior:
1. Set up RMS on a local cluster running k3s
2. Migrate RMS to a local cluster running rke2
3. local cluster running rke2 tries and fails to "upgrade" to k3s, keeping the local cluster in a cordoned state

**Expected behavior**
Migration should be allowed to move to a different local cluster, you should not be limited to the same k8s engine as before

**Additional context**
local cluster definition after applying configs: (cluster running rke2, but now "registered" as a k3s cluster)
[fleet-local.yaml.txt](https://github.com/rancher/backup-restore-operator/files/12345233/fleet-local.yaml.txt)

comment.body: How did we determine that? This certainly appears to be a rancher issue rather than a distro issue, I don't know there's anything we can do from the distro side?
